english:
  title: Postscript to A Miscellaneous Refutation of Buddhism
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |
    On a leisure day, I composed fifteen essays titled "A Miscellaneous Refutation of Buddhism," along with four essays on "Historical Records of Former Ages." Once completed, a visitor read them and said: "In your refutation of the Buddhist doctrine of transmigration, you cite the principle of perpetual generation in all things to elucidate it. Your argument seems plausible. However, the Buddhist teaching states: 'All insentient things arise from the realm of dharma-nature, while all sentient beings arise from the Buddha-womb. Therefore, all creatures with blood and vital force share one consciousness, and all with consciousness share one Buddha-nature.' Yet you conflate the sentient and insentient without discrimination. Is this not merely expending words and breath, falling into the fault of forced interpretation and arbitrary attachment?"

    I replied: "Alas, this is precisely what Mencius meant by establishing two roots. Yet the qi pervading heaven and earth is fundamentally one. It divides into yin and yang through movement and stillness, and manifests the five phases through transformation and combination. As Zhou Zi said: 'The five phases are one yin-yang, and yin-yang are one Supreme Ultimate.' Between movement, stillness, transformation, and combination, what flows forth exhibits differences of permeability and obstruction, bias and rectitude. Those obtaining permeability and rectitude become humans; those obtaining obstruction and bias become things. Among the obstructed and biased, those obtaining slight permeability become birds and beasts; those obtaining none become plants and trees. Thus the distinction between sentient and insentient things arises. Zhou Zi also said: 'To move without moving, to feel without feeling—this is spirit.' Because its qi is unobstructed everywhere, it is called spirit. 'To move without stillness, to be still without movement—this is thing.' Because it is confined to form and qi, unable to interpenetrate, it is called thing. What moves without stillness possesses sentience; what is still without movement lacks sentience. Yet both sentient and insentient things arise from this very qi—how can they be called two? Furthermore, in the human body, the hun and po souls, five viscera, eyes, ears, mouth, and nose possess consciousness and movement, while hair and nails lack them. Yet within one body, some parts follow from sentient parents and some from insentient parents. Does this mean we have two parents?"

    The visitor said: "Your words are correct. However, these various refutations venture into the subtleties of human nature, destiny, virtue, and the mysteries of yin-yang and cosmic transformation—matters that even beginning scholars cannot fully grasp, let alone the ignorant masses. I fear that though your explanations are refined, you merely invite criticism for excessive argumentation, bringing no benefit to either Buddhist or Confucian teaching. Moreover, though Buddhist doctrine lacks evidential foundation, worldly ears and eyes have grown accustomed to it. I doubt mere words can overturn it. How much more so when their so-called miraculous radiations of light, relic divisions, and bodily transformations often occur, which is precisely why the vulgar marvel at such strangeness and offer their faith? What argument can you marshal against these?"

    I replied: "Regarding the refutations of transmigration and suchlike, I have already discussed them fully. Though the blindness runs deep and sudden awakening may not come, perhaps one or two devoted scholars, taking my words as inspiration, will reflect and thereby attain understanding. I shall not belabor this further. As for the matter of radiating light and relics, have I no explanation? The mind is the most refined and luminous aspect of qi. The Buddhist monks, regardless of whether their thoughts are wholesome or unwholesome, right or wrong, endlessly strip away layer upon layer, constantly drawing inward. Since the mind is inherently a luminous thing, and they concentrate their essence in this manner, what accumulates within naturally radiates outward—this follows the natural order. Why marvel at the Buddha's radiant light? Furthermore, Heaven generates this mind precisely because of its supreme spirituality and brightness—to govern the body and mysteriously order all principles, to direct all things—not as some superfluous ornament. It resembles Heaven's gift of fire, originally intended for human benefit. Yet if someone buries fire in ashes so that the cold cannot warm themselves and the hungry cannot cook, what benefit comes from flames dancing above the ash, however bright? This is why I do not value the Buddha's radiating light.

    Moreover, fire as a thing endures only through constant use. If buried in ash and not regularly tended, however fierce initially, it inevitably turns to ash and extinguishes. So too with the human mind—it lives only through constant practice of worry, vigilance, and careful deliberation, whereupon righteousness arises. Should one merely gather it inward and seal it away, then despite appearing bright, it must wither into silent extinction. What seemed luminous becomes obscurity. This is something one cannot afford to ignore.

    As for statues radiating light—rotten grass and decayed wood possess phosphorescence at night. Why doubt this alone? That humans possess relics is like snakes and clams possessing pearls. Even among those called 'virtuous teachers,' some possess no relics—they are like snakes and clams without pearls. The world reports that when someone preserves a clam's pearl without boring or steaming it, after long years when taken out, additional pearls have grown. This demonstrates that where life-vitality persists, natural increase occurs—such is the principle. The Buddha's division of relics follows the same pattern. If one claims the Buddha, supremely spiritual, is moved by human sincerity to divide relics, then Buddhist monks, who preserve their teachers' hair and bones in great quantity, why through earnest petition do they not request these to be divided? Why only speak of relic division? This is nothing but material nature—what else could it be?

    Some say: 'Relic means hardness—iron cannot break it; this proves its spirituality.' Yet strike it with an antelope horn and it shatters to dust. Why would relics be harder than iron yet softer than horn? This is merely material property; nothing strange about it. When two sticks are rubbed or iron and stone struck together, fire emerges—yet this requires human effort. But take a fire-essence pearl, angle it toward the sun with mugwort as tinder, and smoke rises and flames leap forth without human intervention. Initially appearing as mere flickering sparks, finally it blazes bright enough to ignite Kunlun's summit, burning jade and stone alike. How miraculous this seems! Yet is this not also merely material nature? Or is there a spiritual essence dwelling in obscurity, responding to human sincerity to bring this about?

    The benefits fire brings are tremendous. Cooking hardens things to softness. Heating warms the cold. Medicinal herbs become digestible; the hungry are satisfied, the sick healed. Fire melts metal to forge plows, axes, cauldrons for human livelihood, swords and spears for military might. Fire's genesis is so miraculous, its utility so immense—yet you hold none of this precious, while relics, useless to clothe the cold or feed the hungry, unable to serve as weapons or medicine, you revere! Should the Buddha grant thousands through a single prayer, finding them worthless, would you not cast them into water and fire, severing their very roots? Yet you bow before them in devotion? Alas, that people abandon real benefit for empty strangeness, abandon substance for vanity—is this not cause for lamentation?"

    The visitor, moved beyond himself, prostrated and said: "Now hearing your words, I understand that Confucian teaching is correct and Buddhist doctrine is false. Your words surpass even Yang Xiong. Therefore I record this at the scroll's end as a complete account."
